{"term":"1957","caseName":"United States v. New York, New Haven & Hartford Railroad Company","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/45","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 20, 1957 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13404","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Continuing in the line of answer to the question of Mr. Justice Brennan.","start":0,"stop":9.819,"duration":9.82},{"text":"I'd like to say that our position is that there was no real significant change in the responsibilities before or of after 322.","start":9.819,"stop":19.805,"duration":9.99},{"text":"But that I mean this, it is true that before 322 the Government could take its good time about determining whether it owed the money.","start":19.805,"stop":34.83,"duration":15.02},{"text":"But my point and our point here is that that was not a final determination.","start":34.83,"stop":40.732,"duration":5.9},{"text":"If the carrier did not like that, the carrier could go into Court and some judicial tribunal will determine whether or not that was a proper payment by the Government.","start":40.732,"stop":53.354,"duration":12.62}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Who has the burden of proof on --","start":53.354,"stop":54.919,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"In that case, Your Honor, the burden of proof would be on the railroad.","start":54.919,"stop":59.019,"duration":4.1},{"text":"And after 322, the railroads could go in and sue on the amount deducted that is, they could've gone in and sued on this $1025.","start":59.019,"stop":71.752,"duration":12.73},{"text":"And if they have then it would have been up to the railroads to prove their case.","start":71.752,"stop":78.037,"duration":6.29},{"text":"We are not saying in any way that the railroad should be relieved from the burden of proving their case.","start":78.037,"stop":87.53,"duration":9.49},{"text":"We are simply saying that when the railroad sues for one bill and the Government convened by way of affirmative defense at its set off.","start":87.53,"stop":101.138,"duration":13.61},{"text":"We are saying that the railroad does not have the burden of disproving the Government's case.","start":101.138,"stop":108.611,"duration":7.47},{"text":"And conversely, the Government does have the real burden of proving that its counterclaim in set off is valid.","start":108.611,"stop":117.196,"duration":8.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You know what's valid (Inaudible)","start":117.196,"stop":122.923,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Justice, no.","start":122.923,"stop":124.278,"duration":1.36},{"text":"We -- we --","start":124.278,"stop":124.947,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It's valid on the claims from which it was deducted.","start":124.947,"stop":128.208,"duration":3.26}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we would and we would do that just as a matter of -- of practical mechanics of a -- of a suit.","start":128.208,"stop":138.926,"duration":10.72},{"text":"First of all Mr. Justice, may I explain that -- I don't know how to explain it because I know, you know more about than I do, but there's nothing mystical about a 322 transaction between the Government and the railroads.","start":138.926,"stop":155.854,"duration":16.93},{"text":"They do not at all act at arm's length.","start":155.854,"stop":158.567,"duration":2.71},{"text":"First of all, the railroad and the Government both employed very experienced, highly trained personnel in rates and divisions classification.","start":158.567,"stop":171.141,"duration":12.57},{"text":"And when the Government says that they have overpaid the railroad, the railroad looked it over and there is a -- an amicable interchange of their opinion.","start":171.141,"stop":182.798,"duration":11.66},{"text":"And I would say that possibly at least 95% of the cases where there is a deduction under 322, there is an amicable adjustment.","start":182.798,"stop":194.321,"duration":11.52},{"text":"Now, actually in the case here before us today, that -- that very so -- same thing happened.","start":194.321,"stop":199.565,"duration":5.24},{"text":"They deducted $1025.","start":199.565,"stop":203.695,"duration":4.13},{"text":"After looking the thing over, the railroad agreed that all but $402, it was a proper deduction.","start":203.695,"stop":212.339,"duration":8.64},{"text":"Likewise, the Government agreed, too, that in part of it that Service Order 68 did not apply.","start":212.339,"stop":220.031,"duration":7.69},{"text":"So you see, it's one of those things where they -- it's a workable rule and they tried to work out the best they can.","start":220.031,"stop":226.718,"duration":6.69},{"text":"However, we say that it is not fair or just unreasonable to impute to Section 322 the right in the Government when they have come to a stalemate with the railroad, the right in the Government to say, “Well, I listened to you.","start":226.718,"stop":246.435,"duration":19.72},{"text":"You're a nice fellow, but this is it.","start":246.435,"stop":250.028,"duration":3.59},{"text":"We're going to make the determination and we say this.","start":250.028,"stop":253.295,"duration":3.27},{"text":"You either pay us back or else.\"","start":253.295,"stop":255.561,"duration":2.27},{"text":"And the “or else” is the deduction.","start":255.561,"stop":258.134,"duration":2.57},{"text":"We say that in lieu of some -- there is no means of -- for arbitrating these stalemates.","start":258.134,"stop":265.847,"duration":7.71},{"text":"And we say that the only proper tribunal is the one that's left which is the judicial tribunal.","start":265.847,"stop":271.793,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Assuming your premise, the burden of proof is on the Government's situation, what have you to say to the argument is the burden shifts or at least the duty of going to forward shifts, once the Government has shown that -- once the Government has alleged, which in here that there were cars available, that the burden shifts to you because the records necessary to prove this are all in your possession.","start":271.793,"stop":304.281,"duration":32.49}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, first of all, Mr. Justice, I recognize the fact that the burden of going forward could shift and possibly --","start":304.281,"stop":309.486,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is why conventional -- conventional greeting, I suppose.","start":309.486,"stop":313.696,"duration":4.21}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":313.696,"stop":314.143,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Perhaps, the other one could --","start":314.143,"stop":315.7,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"The --","start":315.7,"stop":316.087,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They're not same result.","start":316.087,"stop":317.514,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the burden could shift if it could be shown that there were facts which were peculiarly within the knowledge of the railroad.","start":317.514,"stop":325.237,"duration":7.72},{"text":"Now, actually as -- well, as the case finally developed for the Government now, they are saying that they did, that they did present a prima facie case.","start":325.237,"stop":338.169,"duration":12.93},{"text":"And they are saying that once they simply alleged that the size of the car or that was available that that is sufficient.","start":338.169,"stop":348.657,"duration":10.49},{"text":"And then the burden of going forward shifted to us.","start":348.657,"stop":352.587,"duration":3.93},{"text":"Now, I say this, if they had put in one scintilla of evidence in this case that there were cars of the size available, this -- or the cars of the size ordered available then at least that would have been some indication that they were prepared to assume the burden of proving that counterclaim and it would have been up to the Court to determine within whose province lay the peculiarity of these facts.","start":352.587,"stop":383.012,"duration":30.43},{"text":"Now, in meeting the Government's argument in the railroad's brief, we have pointed out actually and as a matter of fact that in this case, I do not think that the Government could successfully allege that the facts were peculiarly within the knowledge of the railroad, because first of all, the Government who ought to found the relief was very unhappy with the Service Order 68, so unhappy that shortly after it was inaugurated by the ICC, they petitioned to have it waived insofar it applied running Government shipments.","start":383.012,"stop":422.21,"duration":39.2},{"text":"And in that particular petition which by the way it's set out as Exhibit A in the railroad's brief.","start":422.21,"stop":430.457,"duration":8.25},{"text":"In that petition the War Department went to great lengths to show what they were doing to see to it that all facets of the transportation facilities were being used.","start":430.457,"stop":441.779,"duration":11.32},{"text":"And they pointed out that they had made spot inspections and they have this and they have that.","start":441.779,"stop":447.366,"duration":5.59},{"text":"It's quite amply, I submit, setting forth that the Government knew just as much about or whether we had cars available or not, but to get back Your Honor's question, if that had -- if it is true that had the case progressed to the point where the Government was assuming its burden of proof, they might well have come a place in the case where the burden of going forward might have shifted.","start":447.366,"stop":474.723,"duration":27.36}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this is summary judgment, isn't it?","start":474.723,"stop":477.835,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":477.835,"stop":477.993,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"A summary judgment?","start":477.993,"stop":479.059,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":479.059,"stop":479.666,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understand it, the Government said there were cars available prepared to (Inaudible) that.","start":479.666,"stop":486.68,"duration":7.01},{"text":"And you fellows do nothing more under those circumstances in assuming that this is an exception to the burden of proof rule or sufficient to shift the burden, why wouldn't the Government be entitled?","start":486.68,"stop":502.676,"duration":16}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor please, first of all, the -- it isn't -- wasn't quite that way.","start":502.676,"stop":505.983,"duration":3.31},{"text":"It is true that it was summary judgment, but it was summary judgment filed by the plaintiff.","start":505.983,"stop":511.691,"duration":5.71},{"text":"The -- the motion filed by the Government was a motion I didn't quite understand.","start":511.691,"stop":518.645,"duration":6.95},{"text":"It was a motion which said, “We seek judgment for the Government because the plaintiff,” being the railroad, “Has not alleged facts which entitled it to relief.”","start":518.645,"stop":532.011,"duration":13.37},{"text":"Now, the District Court denied that motion and at the same time the railroad had filed a motion for summary judgment claiming that there was no general issue of facts outstanding.","start":532.011,"stop":545.928,"duration":13.92},{"text":"And since we do not believe that the facts of -- whether we knew or they knew more about the availability of the cars, that wasn't alleged to the facts so the Court naturally assume that -- I mean, they decided on the facts that there was no fact outstanding.","start":545.928,"stop":563.423,"duration":17.5},{"text":"So that it was -- there are -- arose in this case.","start":563.423,"stop":566.325,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Sweeney, when this claim was processed, the deduction initially arise that by the Government after they ordered on the post-audit.","start":566.325,"stop":576.62,"duration":10.29},{"text":"Did the Government say, we're entitled of this deduction because the railroad hasn't proved to us they didn't have cars available or was the audit in its position, we know the fact that the railroad did have cars available.","start":576.62,"stop":590.949,"duration":14.33}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Justice, I -- I don't -- I don't know that I ever got the actual facts of that.","start":590.949,"stop":596.536,"duration":5.59},{"text":"My recollection of the record, of the file in the case is that the Government sent out what they call a Form 103 and that form says on it or contains on it the -- the new computation procedure according to the determination of the Government.","start":596.536,"stop":616.882,"duration":20.35},{"text":"And I think it simply said that Service Order 68 did not apply, something to that effect.","start":616.882,"stop":622.571,"duration":5.69},{"text":"I do know that -- that I -- the cars to be served upon them extensive interrogatory, trying to find out some of the answers myself and I do know that in answer to some of my interrogatories, they had said that they didn't think the Service Order applied, Service Order 68 applied in this case.","start":622.571,"stop":640.314,"duration":17.74},{"text":"Now, likewise, speaking of those interrogatories, the only facts upon which the Government relied by the way, Mr. Justice Harlan, the only fact upon which the Government relies, that it has proof, the question of availability to the cars was there own answers to interrogatories.","start":640.314,"stop":660.68,"duration":20.37},{"text":"And -- and I say that's no proof at all.","start":660.68,"stop":662.138,"duration":1.46},{"text":"I mean, that's just a statement in which the Court either could have or did not have to believe.","start":662.138,"stop":668.264,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Sweeney, may I ask you to indicate some other types of controversy that arise between the railroad -- the carriers and the Government?","start":668.264,"stop":679.335,"duration":11.07}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":679.335,"stop":679.832,"duration":0.5},{"text":"There are several --","start":679.832,"stop":679.952,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you shed some light on -- on the question of whether it is -- this is merely the establishment of (Voice Overlap) --","start":679.952,"stop":685.555,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, one --","start":685.555,"stop":685.643,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That will indicate the rule of going forward.","start":685.643,"stop":688.116,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, --","start":688.116,"stop":688.164,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What are the types of controversy?","start":688.164,"stop":689.759,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"One of the big controversies is land grant, of course, out the war situation.","start":689.759,"stop":693.669,"duration":3.91},{"text":"That's land grant whether -- whether the Government paid for transportation over -- over an area that was land granted, that's one of them.","start":693.669,"stop":703.558,"duration":9.89},{"text":"Then classifications --","start":703.558,"stop":703.658,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":703.658,"stop":704.986,"duration":1.33},{"text":"-- we stop a minute there.","start":704.986,"stop":707.878,"duration":2.89},{"text":"That's rather a question of law, isn't it?","start":707.878,"stop":709.513,"duration":1.63},{"text":"(Inaudible) whether -- whether the shipment could have been sent over land grant there for just cheap arrangements.","start":709.513,"stop":715.978,"duration":6.46}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":715.978,"stop":716.794,"duration":0.82},{"text":"It's a question of fact, if Your Honor please, I think as to whether any particular mileage --","start":716.794,"stop":722.373,"duration":5.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":722.373,"stop":722.573,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of railroad was land granted.","start":722.573,"stop":724.647,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that --","start":724.647,"stop":725.703,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"And that were --","start":725.703,"stop":726.659,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that -- there's no -- you keep your knowledge on anybody.","start":726.659,"stop":728.905,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's right.","start":728.905,"stop":730.39,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what else?","start":730.39,"stop":731.137,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, another type would be -- well, such as they had in the Western Pacific case, the question of whether or not an incendiary bomb was an incendiary bomb.","start":731.137,"stop":742.801,"duration":11.66},{"text":"In other words, whether a shallow case --","start":742.801,"stop":744.655,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Classification, you mean, classification problem.","start":744.655,"stop":745.903,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Classification -- classification problem would be another one.","start":745.903,"stop":754.512,"duration":8.61},{"text":"Well, rates and division such as we have in -- sometimes, when we have these explosives sent from the West Coast to Boston for example and they had to be backed up during the war.","start":754.512,"stop":766.861,"duration":12.35},{"text":"They were -- they had what they call backup deck all the way from a large metropolitan area.","start":766.861,"stop":771.482,"duration":4.62},{"text":"And the question is to whether there were rates and divisions involved in that as to whether the Government through a Section 20 -- quotation 22 rate paid the proper amount, those are the examples --","start":771.482,"stop":782.678,"duration":11.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Demurrage problems?","start":782.678,"stop":785.912,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it could be.","start":785.912,"stop":787.247,"duration":1.33},{"text":"It -- it -- demurrage problems could be, but I don't --","start":787.247,"stop":789.722,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":789.722,"stop":790.152,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't recall of any.","start":790.152,"stop":791.318,"duration":1.17},{"text":"I never recall of any.","start":791.318,"stop":791.635,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the Accounting Office a division for -- vis-à-vis the railroads?","start":791.635,"stop":799.031,"duration":7.4}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think they do, Your Honor, because every time that we go to the GAO, we meet the same nice gentlemen that are there and they -- I think they -- they're experts.","start":799.031,"stop":808.45,"duration":9.42},{"text":"They --","start":808.45,"stop":809.348,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they're not nice -- nice, this isn't restricted to that particular graph of the Accounting Office, is it?","start":809.348,"stop":814.457,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think it's -- I think the Accounting Office --","start":814.457,"stop":816.483,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Generally nice.","start":816.483,"stop":817.172,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"-- throughout is generally nice.","start":817.172,"stop":818.507,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":818.507,"stop":818.797,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly, but my contact has been with that particular group.","start":818.797,"stop":827.032,"duration":8.24},{"text":"Section -- the -- the history of 322 --","start":827.032,"stop":830.633,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr.-- Mr. Sweeney, before you get to the history, would you answer me this please.","start":830.633,"stop":839.069,"duration":8.44},{"text":"Do I -- am I correct in believing that the tariff for this commodity that was being transported would have been lower, the math which the railroad charged, if the railroad had had the proper size cars for it?","start":839.069,"stop":862.606,"duration":23.54}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":862.606,"stop":863.372,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And that if they didn't have the cars for it and had to -- had to use a larger one, but then the Government would have to -- have to pay the tariff for the larger car.","start":863.372,"stop":875.727,"duration":12.36}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":875.727,"stop":876.883,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what -- what I want to ask is this.","start":876.883,"stop":880.733,"duration":3.85},{"text":"How could the Government be expected to know and to prove that your railroad didn't have cars on that particular day of the particular size that were called for, for the lower tariff?","start":880.733,"stop":899.26,"duration":18.53}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Because, Your Honor, the -- the transportation during the war as you know was conducted by the transportation corps and they had a man assigned to each area and those were the persons who ordered the cars.","start":899.26,"stop":912.953,"duration":13.69},{"text":"Now, at any time -- at any time that the -- first of all, these cars were not loaded by the railroad, they were given over to a Government train.","start":912.953,"stop":925.26,"duration":12.31},{"text":"They have a depot of some sort where they were being loaded.","start":925.26,"stop":929.212,"duration":3.95},{"text":"Now, at any time that the cars came in there, they did not necessarily come in, in the one, two, three order that they were ordered on the bill of lading, say of yesterday, because that would have been almost impossible.","start":929.212,"stop":943.17,"duration":13.96},{"text":"So, if they ordered 10 cars, the 10 cars were shifted over to them as they came in and the Government had its own selection of the number of cars that come in to its own depot as to which one they'd use first or which one they'd use second.","start":943.17,"stop":956.922,"duration":13.75},{"text":"Now, if at anytime the safety army for example, if the army had received the cars in response to its orders, which cars were not in the size ordered, they could have refused to accept those cars and made the railroad determine whether or not they had them.","start":956.922,"stop":980.126,"duration":23.2},{"text":"We -- I -- I think it is only reasonable to keep in mind in this context that the furnishing of Government or cars to the Government during the war was a tremendous problem.","start":980.126,"stop":992.649,"duration":12.52},{"text":"And thus, it was one of those things where I think everybody just did the best they could to get along the best they could and it was only some six years afterwards, the two examiners in the GAO Office determined that we didn't have these cars.","start":992.649,"stop":1012.754,"duration":20.11},{"text":"As I read the Rule 34, now Rule 34 is in the -- it's ordered in classification number 14 and that is the one that has the rule in it that says that if the Government is unable to furnish a car of the size ordered, then it must charge only -- that it must charge with the size of the car furnished if the goods which are to be transported will not fit on the size of the car ordered.","start":1012.754,"stop":1048.96,"duration":36.21},{"text":"Now, that was a good rule.","start":1048.96,"stop":1050.575,"duration":1.62},{"text":"Now, Service Order 68 which is the basis of this case waived that rule.","start":1050.575,"stop":1055.922,"duration":5.35},{"text":"And the result of Service Order 68 was this, that if the Government was unable -- if the railroad is unable to furnish the Government with a car of the size ordered then irrespective of whether or not the goods to be shipped could be shipped on that size or could not be shipped on that size the Government still paid for the size of the car furnished.","start":1055.922,"stop":1079.224,"duration":23.3},{"text":"And I think it's real to point out here that this was not a rule put in by the railroad.","start":1079.224,"stop":1085.22,"duration":6},{"text":"This is a rule put in by the ICC.","start":1085.22,"stop":1087.65,"duration":2.43},{"text":"And in the petition by the Secretary of War to have this Service Order 68 defended as to the Government which is appendix A in our brief.","start":1087.65,"stop":1098.229,"duration":10.58},{"text":"It is -- it is pointed out there that this was not to -- this is not something which the railroad had done and that it was something that the ICC had put in and that it was necessary even though the Government would suffer some additional payments for the larger size ordered.","start":1098.229,"stop":1123.225,"duration":25},{"text":"We think that it's -- I -- I sincerely think that it was just as easy for all the -- and under those circumstances, just as easy for the Government to prove the availability of the car -- size of the car or the size ordered as it was for the railroad.","start":1123.225,"stop":1139.522,"duration":16.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask you this, Mr. Sweeney, this -- plainly be a stupid question, but didn't the Government made this claim and didn't send the available cheaper car -- cheaper cost cars, they must have had some basis for making that claim.","start":1139.522,"stop":1155.966,"duration":16.44}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think they have never set it forth, but I would assume that the only one that they had made was this.","start":1155.966,"stop":1160.596,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I don't know what it is but I'm asking, they must have had some.","start":1160.596,"stop":1163.101,"duration":2.51},{"text":"They don't just go over there and say, “We got a counterclaim.”","start":1163.101,"stop":1166.102,"duration":3},{"text":"Did they introduce anything at the trial?","start":1166.102,"stop":1168.009,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1168.009,"stop":1168.546,"duration":0.54},{"text":"There isn't -- nothing.","start":1168.546,"stop":1169.233,"duration":0.69},{"text":"You see, they didn't offer anything but --","start":1169.233,"stop":1170.379,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They must have had some basis.","start":1170.379,"stop":1171.529,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I'm -- I think I know what the basis was and that is that in the bill of lading, they -- there are two little boxes, one entitled, size of car ordered and the other one, size of car furnished.","start":1171.529,"stop":1185.98,"duration":14.45},{"text":"So that any -- keep in mind, this was six years after they were furnished.","start":1185.98,"stop":1189.94,"duration":3.96},{"text":"Some clerk is going through there and they see one box marked 40 feet for all (Inaudible)","start":1189.94,"stop":1196.528,"duration":6.59},{"text":"And they see the next box marked 46 feet for six (Inaudible)","start":1196.528,"stop":1201.029,"duration":4.5},{"text":"That's enough for them.","start":1201.029,"stop":1203.098,"duration":2.07},{"text":"In other words, they -- they assumed just from seeing those two -- two marks, that since we furnished the larger one that we had the other one available.","start":1203.098,"stop":1213.255,"duration":10.16},{"text":"They -- they're using the converse of the rule.","start":1213.255,"stop":1216.037,"duration":2.78},{"text":"That's all that -- that's all I could say (Inaudible)","start":1216.037,"stop":1217.513,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I thought the rule said that they -- they were to get the lower rate unless the railroad could establish that it didn't have that kind of cars and only had the larger ones.","start":1217.513,"stop":1229.328,"duration":11.82}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1229.328,"stop":1229.665,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Am I wrong in that?","start":1229.665,"stop":1230.731,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you're not wrong in the full text.","start":1230.731,"stop":1233.184,"duration":2.45},{"text":"You're wrong in this, Mr. Chief Justice, if I may --","start":1233.184,"stop":1235.06,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it's all right.","start":1235.06,"stop":1236.068,"duration":1.01},{"text":"Go ahead.","start":1236.068,"stop":1237.006,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"That it does not spell out that if the railroad says it does not have the car, it simply says, if the railroad is unable to furnish, and it doesn't say that the railroad has to state that they're unable.","start":1237.006,"stop":1252.55,"duration":15.54},{"text":"And so, I would assume that the rule of regularity would apply here like everything else.","start":1252.55,"stop":1258.78,"duration":6.23},{"text":"In the rule of regularity, you are suppose to -- we were suppose to obey those rules so that if we had a car available, we would give it.","start":1258.78,"stop":1265.684,"duration":6.9},{"text":"And that if we didn't if we didn't have the car available and we furnished the car of the larger size, there would be the inference or the presumption that we didn't have the car of the size ordered.","start":1265.684,"stop":1274.244,"duration":8.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Will that -- that doesn't disprove that they're nice people, but it doesn't seem some other things either.","start":1274.244,"stop":1283.633,"duration":9.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask you one question?","start":1283.633,"stop":1287.453,"duration":3.82},{"text":"Assuming that the burden is on you, either originally or the result of shifting, in the consequence and any of those affected at all by the lapse of time between the --","start":1287.453,"stop":1307.521,"duration":20.07}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes.","start":1307.521,"stop":1308.128,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":1308.128,"stop":1308.445,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice.","start":1308.445,"stop":1309.882,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And the --","start":1309.882,"stop":1311.479,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"You see, we -- we destroy our records at the end of three years.","start":1311.479,"stop":1315.219,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I want to get at.","start":1315.219,"stop":1316.574,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"And we do that by permission of the ICC.","start":1316.574,"stop":1319.958,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that a --","start":1319.958,"stop":1320.235,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Because if we wait six years, we don't have this record and --","start":1320.235,"stop":1323.659,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean that --","start":1323.659,"stop":1324.725,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any --","start":1324.725,"stop":1325.561,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":1325.561,"stop":1326.098,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you raise that in there?","start":1326.098,"stop":1328.022,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"We didn't raise it as a defense, sir, because they never offered to prove our counter -- their counterclaim to the -- as in the lower court.","start":1328.022,"stop":1334.193,"duration":6.17},{"text":"They didn't do anything.","start":1334.193,"stop":1334.992,"duration":0.8},{"text":"We just say that the plaintiff should have -- prove their case.","start":1334.992,"stop":1339.79,"duration":4.8},{"text":"It would have definitely have been raised, Mr. Justice Whittaker --","start":1339.79,"stop":1341.695,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Did it show on this record -- the facts shown in this record that your record has been destroyed?","start":1341.695,"stop":1348.578,"duration":6.88}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it shows, Mr. Justice, in the record but not through our case.","start":1348.578,"stop":1353.436,"duration":4.86},{"text":"It shows, Mr.-- in Mr. Justice McGruder's opinion.","start":1353.436,"stop":1361.503,"duration":8.07},{"text":"He recites Atlantic Coast Line case and he adopts certain language there and I'm pretty sure that the -- I do know that he did adopt the language from the Atlantic Coast Line case in which it said that the Court was satisfied that the records were destroyed.","start":1361.503,"stop":1378.101,"duration":16.6},{"text":"The railroad -- all railroad records were destroyed at the end of three years.","start":1378.101,"stop":1381.634,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You said this is by authorization of the ICC.","start":1381.634,"stop":1385.017,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1385.017,"stop":1385.404,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that a formal order or just an understanding or what?","start":1385.404,"stop":1388.508,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it is -- it's an order of the ICC and I -- I'm not prepared to say that it is a mandatory order that you do it.","start":1388.508,"stop":1395.653,"duration":7.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but I didn't --","start":1395.653,"stop":1396.09,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"It is a permissive order.","start":1396.09,"stop":1397.21,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1397.21,"stop":1397.755,"duration":0.55},{"text":"But it is by a formal order of the Commission, is it?","start":1397.755,"stop":1400.278,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"As my understanding that it is.","start":1400.278,"stop":1401.673,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) -- would you -- would you --","start":1401.673,"stop":1402.36,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, we cannot -- we cannot destroy without their permission, but I will check it up if it's a --","start":1402.36,"stop":1408.136,"duration":5.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's a little -- apart from this case, there's a hiatus there if it's -- is six years a fair gap between performance and post-audits?","start":1408.136,"stop":1419.442,"duration":11.31}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no.","start":1419.442,"stop":1419.899,"duration":0.46},{"text":"Of course, it's not a fair gap.","start":1419.899,"stop":1420.668,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) -- what I'm suggesting is --","start":1420.668,"stop":1422.632,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"But the --","start":1422.632,"stop":1422.971,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- you can destroy, if the Commission authorizes destruction of carrier documents after three years, is that all for the limit?","start":1422.971,"stop":1433.539,"duration":10.57},{"text":"Where was the burden of that?","start":1433.539,"stop":1434.138,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's right, it should, Your Honor.","start":1434.138,"stop":1437.142,"duration":3},{"text":"We -- we of course are in this position, the ICC, as also the Government and I assume that they would want to protect us as well protect the Government in that respect.","start":1437.142,"stop":1447.056,"duration":9.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you be good enough to check that out, wouldn't you, Mr. Sweeney?","start":1447.056,"stop":1448.943,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I would, Your Honor.","start":1448.943,"stop":1453.981,"duration":5.04},{"text":"In the moment of thought that I have left, we respectfully raise that it's not reasonable to say that 322 allows the Government to make a final determination and that where the Government brings their deduction under 322 into a judicial proceeding, they must meet the requirements of any other counterclaimant and therefore they must prove their case.","start":1453.981,"stop":1478.943,"duration":24.96}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rosenthal.","start":1478.943,"stop":1480.361,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":1480.361,"stop":1481.477,"duration":1.12},{"text":"I was commenting upon which Mr. Sweeney finished up with.","start":1481.477,"stop":1484.699,"duration":3.22},{"text":"Of course the Government has never suggested that there is any finality attendant to the post-audit results any more than there was any finality attaching to the administrative determination under the pre-audit procedure.","start":1484.699,"stop":1500.21,"duration":15.51},{"text":"The Government's position is simply that where this -- the post-audit which have been substituted for the pre-audit, where in that post-audit the administrative officials responsible come to the conclusion that there is a question as to the correctness of the bills of the carrier, the carrier is then under an obligation to establish the correctness of those bills and if it does not do it on an administrative level, it has to do it in a judicial level.","start":1500.21,"stop":1526.779,"duration":26.57},{"text":"Now, I'd like if I may to go into a minute to the administrative practice here.","start":1526.779,"stop":1531.719,"duration":4.94},{"text":"When as Mr. Sweeney indicated after the -- the audit is conducted, if the General Accounting Office has a question as to the correctness of the bill, they send out this form 1003.","start":1531.719,"stop":1542.756,"duration":11.04},{"text":"The carrier upon receive of that form enters into or has the -- certainly, the ability to enter into negotiations with the General Accounting Office.","start":1542.756,"stop":1554.702,"duration":11.95},{"text":"If it's got evidence satisfactory establishing the validity of their claim, it has the opportunity to present that evidence.","start":1554.702,"stop":1560.838,"duration":6.14},{"text":"It's the same thing as under the pre-audit procedure.","start":1560.838,"stop":1563.221,"duration":2.38},{"text":"If under the pre-audit, the question had risen, the carrier was advised and it could then present its proof.","start":1563.221,"stop":1570.116,"duration":6.89},{"text":"The question here is whether carrier does not establish its claim.","start":1570.116,"stop":1575.615,"duration":5.5},{"text":"Who has then in the subsequent judicial proceeding the burden?","start":1575.615,"stop":1580.571,"duration":4.96},{"text":"And of course, the carrier is not required in a judicial proceeding of this kind to show that on any overall basis it is not indebted to the Government.","start":1580.571,"stop":1588.611,"duration":8.04},{"text":"The carrier knows from its negotiation for the GAO just precisely what bills were issued and just precisely what the nature of that issue is.","start":1588.611,"stop":1597.329,"duration":8.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Really, what you're doing here is saying that although the railroad sued on the 1950 bill, the only issue in the case is the 1944 situation and therefore, the burden is on them?","start":1597.329,"stop":1609.105,"duration":11.78}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the 1950 Bill --","start":1609.105,"stop":1611.169,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right?","start":1611.169,"stop":1611.297,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1611.297,"stop":1611.874,"duration":0.58},{"text":"The 1950 Bill never could have been an issue because Congress in setting up the statutory scheme said that you will deduct from amounts found to be due to carriers.","start":1611.874,"stop":1619.547,"duration":7.67},{"text":"So, when Mr. Sweeney suggest that the railroad is willing to assume its burden, he is saying that the railroad is willing to assume its burden of proving the correctness of a bill which he already knows the Government has not and will not challenge.","start":1619.547,"stop":1632.48,"duration":12.93},{"text":"And that actual -- in actuality, we think this has to be governed by the statutory scheme.","start":1632.48,"stop":1636.839,"duration":4.36},{"text":"Now, the private shipper interestingly enough, he can't make these deductions from subsequent bills.","start":1636.839,"stop":1643.13,"duration":6.29},{"text":"He's in the position where he has to bring the affirmative proceeding.","start":1643.13,"stop":1646.184,"duration":3.05},{"text":"That Congress could have done that with the Government.","start":1646.184,"stop":1648.048,"duration":1.86},{"text":"Congress could have said, “You were paid properly.","start":1648.048,"stop":1650.184,"duration":2.14},{"text":"And if subsequently you think you've been overcharged, you can bring a suit and recover just the way a private shipper has.”","start":1650.184,"stop":1656.69,"duration":6.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where the private shipper is allowed credit if he maybe -- the situation is the same.","start":1656.69,"stop":1661.808,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he's got very brief credit and I don't know whether he --","start":1661.808,"stop":1663.742,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I know, but where he has it, it is the same.","start":1663.742,"stop":1666.726,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I don't think -- I'm not so certain if he could withhold at the end of the credit period of 96 hours.","start":1666.726,"stop":1673.003,"duration":6.28},{"text":"I think he would be required to pay the amount of the bills.","start":1673.003,"stop":1676.095,"duration":3.09},{"text":"I think the ICC doesn't say that you can withhold payment for 96 hours and then not pay at all if you don't think that it --","start":1676.095,"stop":1682.141,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But in theory those 96 hours of some shipments that are -- uncontested and some were --","start":1682.141,"stop":1687.858,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1687.858,"stop":1688.016,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- contested then he can do the same thing.","start":1688.016,"stop":1689.531,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1689.531,"stop":1689.679,"duration":0.15},{"text":"And if he does that, the carrier sues them and the railroad then it has the burden of proof.","start":1689.679,"stop":1693.968,"duration":4.29},{"text":"See, we're the ones that are in the position of having -- we don't have -- we have to pay these bills.","start":1693.968,"stop":1698.776,"duration":4.81},{"text":"We don't have the option of the pre-audit at all.","start":1698.776,"stop":1702.239,"duration":3.46},{"text":"And again of course that the Government was not intended to be placed in the same position as the private shipper as reflected by the deduction provision.","start":1702.239,"stop":1709.7,"duration":7.46},{"text":"And of course Congress has set up, we have had them in our brief, numerous statutory protections to make certain that improper claims are not presented to the Treasury and that the Public Treasury is not rated thereby.","start":1709.7,"stop":1722.771,"duration":13.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask to whether it is the Government's contention that if Rule 34, meaning that the -- the shorter or smaller, whatever they are, the lighter cars, if lighter cars are ordered, then -- and heavier cars are rendered that -- that in itself prove the violation of the rule?","start":1722.771,"stop":1753.106,"duration":30.34}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1753.106,"stop":1753.453,"duration":0.35},{"text":"The -- the Government's position is this --","start":1753.453,"stop":1755.379,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean on that question.","start":1755.379,"stop":1756.657,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Under Rule 34, as -- means this, that the carrier can charge the Government or any other shipper on the basis of the larger cars furnished if, but only if that carrier did not have the smaller car -- smaller cars which were ordered available.","start":1756.657,"stop":1779.323,"duration":22.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And it's the mere furnishing proof.","start":1779.323,"stop":1781.848,"duration":2.52},{"text":"They violated the rule.","start":1781.848,"stop":1783.094,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1783.094,"stop":1783.711,"duration":0.62},{"text":"Well, the furnishing, we submit places the burden upon the carrier to come in and show that we did not supply you what you ordered and what was necessary because we didn't have it available.","start":1783.711,"stop":1798.404,"duration":14.69},{"text":"Now, we don't think that that's any extraordinary burden at all.","start":1798.404,"stop":1801.378,"duration":2.97},{"text":"And of course, the Government transportation officers are in no position to know what the Para Market Railroad happen to have at this time.","start":1801.378,"stop":1807.732,"duration":6.35},{"text":"That is information which is in the railroad's possession.","start":1807.732,"stop":1809.776,"duration":2.04},{"text":"They've got the cars, we don't.","start":1809.776,"stop":1811.67,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, during the war it might be the other way around.","start":1811.67,"stop":1814.055,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but -- if at prima facie, we submit and there was no indication in this record at all that the -- that the Government here was in possession.","start":1814.055,"stop":1823.275,"duration":9.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1823.275,"stop":1823.542,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"It would have been under possession of any in this information.","start":1823.542,"stop":1825.209,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"We know that Congress was, it can take judicial orders to the -- the year in which this happened and what the relationship to the railroad and Government trade was, don't need any evidence on that.","start":1825.209,"stop":1836.461,"duration":11.25}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1836.461,"stop":1839.864,"duration":3.4}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 20, 1957 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13435","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 45, United States of America, Petitioner, versus New York, New Haven & Hartford Railroad Company.","start":0,"stop":9.893,"duration":9.89},{"text":"Mr. Rosenthal.","start":9.893,"stop":11.827,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":11.827,"stop":13.919,"duration":2.09},{"text":"In this case, which is here on certiorari to the First Circuit, this Court is called upon to determine the effect of Section 322 of the Transportation Act of 1940 upon the traditional obligation of common carriers to establish the validity of their claims against the Government.","start":13.919,"stop":32.192,"duration":18.27},{"text":"Section 322, the terms of which are set forth at page 3 of the brief of the United States and which is before this Court last year in the Western Pacific case requires, the Government to pay transportation bills upon presentation prior to audit or settlement by the General Accounting Office.","start":32.192,"stop":52.142,"duration":19.95},{"text":"The Section goes on, however, to reserve the Government the right, should a post-audit disclose an overpayment to deduct the amount thereof from any amount subsequently found to be due to the carrier.","start":52.142,"stop":67.049,"duration":14.91},{"text":"Now, in this case, the Government paid in compliance with the statutory mandate certain bills rendered by respondent promptly upon presentation without any audit.","start":67.049,"stop":76.709,"duration":9.66},{"text":"On the post-audit, and the General Accounting Office questioned the correctness of these bills.","start":76.709,"stop":82.668,"duration":5.96},{"text":"When the respondent failed to resolve the doubts that were raised in this regard and failed to make a refund of the determined overpayment, a deduction was made as authorized by the statute in the payment of a subsequent bill rendered by respondent.","start":82.668,"stop":98.979,"duration":16.31},{"text":"This litigation was then instituted ostensibly on the subsequent bill to recover the deduction.","start":98.979,"stop":105.324,"duration":6.34},{"text":"And the question before this Court is whether the carrier had the burden of demonstrating that the charges for these shipments, this earlier -- earlier transportation services, were correct.","start":105.324,"stop":117.137,"duration":11.81},{"text":"In other words, that they had not overcharged the Government on the bills which had been paid without audit in the first instance.","start":117.137,"stop":123.661,"duration":6.52},{"text":"Now, the underlying facts are simply stated this.","start":123.661,"stop":128.388,"duration":4.73},{"text":"During 1944, the Government ships several carloads of naval property to points on respondent's lines in Massachusetts and Rhode Island.","start":128.388,"stop":136.379,"duration":7.99},{"text":"In each instance the bill of lading called for an open freight car of a particular length.","start":136.379,"stop":141.986,"duration":5.61},{"text":"In each instance, the initial carriers supplied a freight car of a longer length which was unnecessary for the particular services.","start":141.986,"stop":150.029,"duration":8.04},{"text":"And in rendering its bills, the respondent computed each charges on the basis of the minimum weights fixed for the larger car furnished rather than for the cars which had been ordered.","start":150.029,"stop":163.014,"duration":12.99},{"text":"On the post-audit, these facts came to light.","start":163.014,"stop":167.441,"duration":4.43},{"text":"Because no showing was made by respondent that the initial carrier had been unable to supply the ordered cars, which are the only circumstances concededly in which it could bill for the longer furnished cars, the General Accounting Office requested a refund between the charges for the cars ordered and the charges for the cars furnished.","start":167.441,"stop":189.208,"duration":21.77},{"text":"When respondent neither complied with this demand nor explained the failure to furnish the ordered cars, the deduction was made as authorized by Section 322 from amount subsequently found to be due the carrier.","start":189.208,"stop":204.176,"duration":14.97},{"text":"In this case, it was a bill which the carrier had rendered in connection with the 1950 transportation services.","start":204.176,"stop":211.423,"duration":7.25},{"text":"Respondent then sued to recover this amount which had been deducted.","start":211.423,"stop":216.248,"duration":4.82},{"text":"In its complaint, however, it alleged no facts at all, respecting the 1944 shipments upon which the deduction had been predicated.","start":216.248,"stop":224.429,"duration":8.18},{"text":"Instead, the complaint simply alleged the performance of the 1950 service and the rendition of its bill therefore.","start":224.429,"stop":232.295,"duration":7.87}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the time element between the original shipment which is claimed the Government has been overcharged done and the General Accounting Office audit any deduction to the subsequent bill?","start":232.295,"stop":245.742,"duration":13.45}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Approximately six years, Your Honor.","start":245.742,"stop":247.585,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Six years?","start":247.585,"stop":247.941,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"The period -- that period, as Your Honor will recall, of course, this was post war and there was the audit of the bills from the -- the wartime era.","start":247.941,"stop":257.225,"duration":9.28},{"text":"We have some statistics in our brief.","start":257.225,"stop":258.928,"duration":1.7},{"text":"And I think this Court in the Western Pacific case last year refer to similar statistics with respect to the -- the large number of bills that the General Accounting Office would require to audit especially in this -- this period that followed immediately after the war.","start":258.928,"stop":273.575,"duration":14.65},{"text":"I am told now that -- advised by the General Accounting Office that the period necessary for audit has been substantially reduced.","start":273.575,"stop":282.54,"duration":8.97},{"text":"Now, the -- I have indicated the complaint alleged nothing with respect to this 1944 shipments, alleged simply the performance of the 1950 shipments.","start":282.54,"stop":291.97,"duration":9.43},{"text":"In its answer, the Government admitted the performance of the 1950 shipment and the correctness of the charges for that shipment.","start":291.97,"stop":299.704,"duration":7.73},{"text":"The answer went on, however, to plea Section 322 as a statutory defense.","start":299.704,"stop":306.17,"duration":6.47},{"text":"The words -- the answer pleaded that as authorized by the statute, the Government had adjusted the 1944 bills by deducting from the amount due on the 1950 bill.","start":306.17,"stop":319.783,"duration":13.61},{"text":"It explained the basis of the determination of overpayment.","start":319.783,"stop":322.656,"duration":2.87},{"text":"It went onto alleged that the respondent had never supplied for the Government with any facts respecting the availability of the cars which had been ordered.","start":322.656,"stop":331.496,"duration":8.84},{"text":"The respondent there filed a response in which he had been -- in which is denied that it had overcharged the Government on this 1944 shipments.","start":331.496,"stop":340.372,"duration":8.88},{"text":"And the issue was thus narrowed to the correctness of the charges for those 1944 shipments, in other words, to the merits of the administrative adjustment which the Government had made pursuant to the statute.","start":340.372,"stop":355.559,"duration":15.19},{"text":"Now, both of the courts below have held that the burden of establishing the essential facts on this issue, the facts on the merits of the Government's defense based upon the statute rested upon the United States.","start":355.559,"stop":369.492,"duration":13.93},{"text":"And we submit, if it please the Court, that this holding is an error.","start":369.492,"stop":374.122,"duration":4.63},{"text":"Now, we think that fundamental to any discussion of the burden approved question is the long established principle that a claimant against the Government has the burden of establishing the validity of its claim.","start":374.122,"stop":389.244,"duration":15.12},{"text":"Now, traditionally, the -- the protection of the public treasury, bills submitted in connection with the rendition of a contractual service for the United States have been audited prior to payment under rulings of the Comptroller General recognized by the Court of Claims as far back as the 1880s.","start":389.244,"stop":407.643,"duration":18.4},{"text":"In connection with this pre-payment examination, it is incumbent upon the claimant to produce evidence satisfactory establishing that claim.","start":407.643,"stop":415.653,"duration":8.01},{"text":"If it doesn't produce that evidence, the evidence leaves some doubt as to the validity of the claim.","start":415.653,"stop":421.9,"duration":6.25},{"text":"The claim is not paid and the claim is recourse as a suit under the Tucker Act.","start":421.9,"stop":426.223,"duration":4.32},{"text":"The Court of Claims has continually held in such a suit the claimant's burden as the same as on the administrative level.","start":426.223,"stop":431.688,"duration":5.46},{"text":"It must alleged and proved the facts establishing clear liability in the part of United States for the amount assertedly due to the claimant.","start":431.688,"stop":439.348,"duration":7.66},{"text":"Now, prior to the enactment of the Transportation Act of 1940, these procedures were concededly applicable to common carriers as well as to all other claimants.","start":439.348,"stop":448.627,"duration":9.28},{"text":"The carrier was paid only that amount which the preaudit determined it was entitled to it.","start":448.627,"stop":453.94,"duration":5.31},{"text":"It must be satisfied with the results of the preaudit.","start":453.94,"stop":457.031,"duration":3.09},{"text":"It could bring suit under the Tucker Act and in that suit, it would have the obligation of demonstrating that its bills were correct and that the Comptroller General's determination was in error.","start":457.031,"stop":466.981,"duration":9.95},{"text":"So we say that the issue here really narrows it down to this, and that is whether Section 322, by substituting a post-audit for a preaudit procedure was intended to or does in fact operate to relieve the carrier of this traditional obligation, which today is concededly applies to all other claimants against the United States.","start":466.981,"stop":492.737,"duration":25.76},{"text":"Now, in our brief, we set forth in some detail the background of the legislative history of Section 322.","start":492.737,"stop":500.038,"duration":7.3},{"text":"In sum, it is this.","start":500.038,"stop":502.242,"duration":2.2},{"text":"If the section is -- was designed to serve a single purpose of enabling common carriers to obtain prompt payment on their bills.","start":502.242,"stop":511.667,"duration":9.42},{"text":"It was inserted in the Transportation Act solely because of the insistence of industry spokesman that the delays attendant to the prepayment audit of bills was -- gave rise to economic hardship.","start":511.667,"stop":527.042,"duration":15.38},{"text":"There wasn't the slightest intimation anywhere that the Government's right to require the carrier to establish a doubtful claim would be, in any wise, affected by the conversion from the preaudit to the post-audit procedure.","start":527.042,"stop":541.554,"duration":14.51},{"text":"To the contrary, it appears that all concerned believed that the public treasury would be fully protected by the right of deduction that was expressly placed in the statute.","start":541.554,"stop":551.405,"duration":9.85},{"text":"The only inference, we submit, that the legislative history of this section permits is that the carriers were to receive the benefit of prompt payment but that the Government was to retain an impaired the right should a post-audit indicate to the Comptroller General that there was a basis for doing so, to put these carriers to their approval.","start":551.405,"stop":572.309,"duration":20.9},{"text":"Now, in this connection, we think it is of no little significance that the Association of American Railroads, itself, the industry spokesman for the railroads, in seeking executive support for this change from the preaudit to the post-audit procedure indicated that if the Government pay bills upon presentation without examination to determine whether they were correct and should they subsequently determine that there had been an overpayment, the carrier would refund the amount of the -- administratively determine over -- overpayment reserving the right, of course, to bring suit in the Court of Claims if it were dissatisfied with the Comptroller General's determination.","start":572.309,"stop":615.779,"duration":43.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Does -- does that mean, if I understand it correctly, that your view that there's a 322 deduction on bill A, along comes the railroad and three years later, choose on bill B, you say that the railroad has to allege as part of its cause of action on bill B that there are no valid offsets --","start":615.779,"stop":648.352,"duration":32.57}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no.","start":648.352,"stop":648.366,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- against those charges?","start":648.366,"stop":649.871,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, the railroad knows when the deduction is made, the railroad is appraised of the particular bill --","start":649.871,"stop":658.249,"duration":8.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":658.249,"stop":659.943,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"-- previous bill which was administratively determined to have contained an overpayment --","start":659.943,"stop":666.25,"duration":6.31}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":666.25,"stop":666.828,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and which is, therefore, the subject of this particular deduction, to the railroad knows precisely why the deduction has been made.","start":666.828,"stop":674.477,"duration":7.65},{"text":"Now, it is our position that the railroad, when it brings suit then to recover the amount of the deduction which is made from these amounts subsequently found to be --","start":674.477,"stop":683.18,"duration":8.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'm talking about to recover the amount of a new bill not the deduction.","start":683.18,"stop":688.564,"duration":5.38}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but that's what the suit, in effect, Your Honor, is to recover the -- the deduction which was made because of the administrative adjustment on the earlier bill.","start":688.564,"stop":699.721,"duration":11.16}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- yes, but it's the consequence of that when it wants to recover on a new bill as to which there is no dispute about the deduction that it also has to alleged and prove that there are no amounts owning by it to the Government or offsets with the Government had claimed in respect to prior bills.","start":699.721,"stop":720.007,"duration":20.29}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"To -- well, Your Honor, the Government, in this case, when the railroad suit on its original -- on this 1950 bill, the Government set up a statutory defense.","start":720.007,"stop":730.404,"duration":10.4},{"text":"It -- it set up the defense that on this bill, it exercises the right which it concededly has under the statute to adjust the 1944 bills through the vehicle of this 1950 bill.","start":730.404,"stop":746.228,"duration":15.82},{"text":"Now, this is the defense, we submit.","start":746.228,"stop":747.705,"duration":1.48},{"text":"It is not a counterclaim.","start":747.705,"stop":749.222,"duration":1.52},{"text":"We are defending on a basis that we had --","start":749.222,"stop":750.664,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's a conventional offset.","start":750.664,"stop":752.663,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we -- it's -- it's a particular right which is conferred upon us by -- expressly by this statute.","start":752.663,"stop":759.925,"duration":7.26},{"text":"Now, our position is that at that point, the -- what the -- the real issue here, what it narrows itself down to is whether or not in this particular instance, the Comptroller General properly or improperly exercised this right which the statute concededly confers upon him.","start":759.925,"stop":780.646,"duration":20.72},{"text":"That is the -- the issue.","start":780.646,"stop":781.726,"duration":1.08},{"text":"And I -- we submit that then the carrier to meet our defense must show that the Comptroller General improperly deducted these amounts.","start":781.726,"stop":791.373,"duration":9.65},{"text":"Now, the result below -- below, of course, relieves the -- the common carriers once and for all, for all times, of ever establishing the validity of these claims which were paid upon presentation and the legislative history does -- does not, of course, indicates that that was nothing intend of Congress.","start":791.373,"stop":811.675,"duration":20.3},{"text":"Furthermore, if Congress had intended that the carrier could come in -- ostensibly on the second bill and thereby relieved itself once and for all of any obligation to prove the correctness of the original charges, Congress would not have inserted this deduction provision at all.","start":811.675,"stop":829.603,"duration":17.93},{"text":"The Congress wanted to place upon the Government, wanted to change the whole system and place upon the Government in the future, insofar as common carriers are concerned, the obligation to disprove the correctness of railroad charges it wouldn't have provided for deduction.","start":829.603,"stop":842.185,"duration":12.58},{"text":"All that it need to do was say that the carriers to be paid promptly.","start":842.185,"stop":846.107,"duration":3.92},{"text":"And then if the Government was dissatisfied with the results of the -- the prompt payment that the Government on the audit came to the conclusion that there was no repayment, the Government then could affirmatively bring suit under Section 1345 of Title 28.","start":846.107,"stop":862.158,"duration":16.05},{"text":"And we think that not only the legislative history but indeed, the terms of statute itself set up the statutory scheme that the carrier cannot hide behind the -- the subsequent bill.","start":862.158,"stop":874.097,"duration":11.94},{"text":"And I might note in that connection that Congress did -- obviously did not intend, in any of instances, that there would be any dispute as to the bill which served as the basis for making the deduction because going back to the terms of 322 once more, the section says that the amount may be deducted from any amounts subsequently found to be due the carrier.","start":874.097,"stop":896.503,"duration":22.41},{"text":"So in none of these instances would there ever be any dispute with respect to the bill that -- that served as the basis for the deduction.","start":896.503,"stop":904.929,"duration":8.43},{"text":"And we submit that the carrier cannot, consistently with the statutory scheme, command and allege this or ostensibly bring suit upon this -- this later bill and then sit back and say it is up to the Government to disprove that -- to prove that our earlier bills were incorrect.","start":904.929,"stop":926.095,"duration":21.17},{"text":"And we say in the first instance, true enough they can do it as they did here, but we have the right to plea, not as counterclaim but as a statutory defense, that what we did is authorized by the statute.","start":926.095,"stop":936.767,"duration":10.67},{"text":"It is a necessary result of the change from the preaudit to the post-audit procedure.And as you will --","start":936.767,"stop":943.535,"duration":6.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Judge Magruder points out you'd had that right to deduct the part of statute as a right to common law.","start":943.535,"stop":950.435,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is quite true but the -- that the Congress felt it necessary here to reiterate it expressly where that common law right, of course, is -- at all times existed, we think, emphasizes the congressional view that this was going -- was to be in the nature of a conditional payment that the railroads were to get all of the money on their bills promptly.","start":950.435,"stop":972.337,"duration":21.9},{"text":"And in most instances, of course, there's no challenge.","start":972.337,"stop":974.547,"duration":2.21},{"text":"And the --","start":974.547,"stop":974.773,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Before Justice Harlan interrupted you, if I'm -- I understood you indicated that 322 does something affirmative rather make the reservation of a preexisting common law right.","start":974.773,"stop":986.135,"duration":11.36}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"No, 322, we -- we submit, does this.","start":986.135,"stop":990.548,"duration":4.41},{"text":"It reflects the congressional intent that while the carriers are to be paid promptly in presentation should be subsequently that the Comptroller General, on the post-audit, determine that there has been an overpayment, that the Government then can put itself into the position -- the status quo ante and put itself into the position that would have occupied as to those bills as to which there are some questions.","start":990.548,"stop":1012.6,"duration":22.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What you are thinking that -- that after first 322, is the same permission (Inaudible) prior to the 322.","start":1012.6,"stop":1018.708,"duration":6.11}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1018.708,"stop":1019.136,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that what you're saying?","start":1019.136,"stop":1020.181,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"It is -- it is permitted to place itself into the same position as to those bills as to which there are some question.","start":1020.181,"stop":1026.906,"duration":6.72},{"text":"Of course, that's a relatively small percentage of the bills that it would have been under the old procedure had it been able to audit the bills in advance.","start":1026.906,"stop":1036.496,"duration":9.59},{"text":"And that is the protection.","start":1036.496,"stop":1037.467,"duration":0.97},{"text":"It's a very sensible protection because the -- the major complaint of the carriers under the preexisting procedure was after all they render millions of bills and most of those bills are -- are clearly correct, that they weren't getting paid for years even on the bills as to which there would be no dispute because of this preaudit.","start":1037.467,"stop":1055.219,"duration":17.75},{"text":"Under this procedure, they collect an old bill.","start":1055.219,"stop":1057.868,"duration":2.65},{"text":"As to most of them, there will be no dispute.","start":1057.868,"stop":1059.971,"duration":2.1},{"text":"As to those bills which there is a dispute, then they have to restore the Government to the -- restore the status quo prior to payment and reserving, of course, this right.","start":1059.971,"stop":1070.468,"duration":10.5},{"text":"And that's what these carriers were seeking as the -- as the Association of American Railroads' position indicates.","start":1070.468,"stop":1076.544,"duration":6.08}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1076.544,"stop":1099.913,"duration":23.37}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1099.913,"stop":1100.467,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1100.467,"stop":1100.999,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1100.999,"stop":1102.416,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1102.416,"stop":1109.803,"duration":7.39}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1109.803,"stop":1112.556,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1112.556,"stop":1120.754,"duration":8.2}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- we submit, Your Honor, that we did not.","start":1120.754,"stop":1124.475,"duration":3.72},{"text":"That -- that what we -- the Comptroller General has authorized and this Court recognized last year in the Western Pacific case to make a unilateral setoff and a unilateral basis.","start":1124.475,"stop":1135.146,"duration":10.67},{"text":"We defended on the ground that we have done exactly what the statute authorizes to do.","start":1135.146,"stop":1139.702,"duration":4.56},{"text":"Now, as -- as far back as the Grand Trunk Western case, this Court indicated that before making deductions, and this was even absent the -- the special considerations which are present because of 322, that making a deduction that the fiscal officers of the Government do not need to first go into court to establish that their deduction is correct.","start":1139.702,"stop":1160.201,"duration":20.5},{"text":"They are entitled to do it unilaterally.","start":1160.201,"stop":1162.621,"duration":2.42},{"text":"Now, the Government did that unilaterally here.","start":1162.621,"stop":1164.393,"duration":1.77},{"text":"It had the perfect right to do it.","start":1164.393,"stop":1166.653,"duration":2.26},{"text":"Now, that represents this issue then.","start":1166.653,"stop":1169.047,"duration":2.39},{"text":"And what the -- what the respondent's recovery is conditioned upon is that in this particular instance, the Comptroller General did not properly exercise that right.","start":1169.047,"stop":1181.241,"duration":12.19},{"text":"Now, we would again like to -- to stress that their -- both the -- the reservation of the provision for deduction and we think also the legislative history itself indicates that the Congress did not intend to transfer as to this very limited special class of all the claimants against the Government to transfer the burden unto the Government to disprove their claims.","start":1181.241,"stop":1207.76,"duration":26.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask if one of the (Inaudible)","start":1207.76,"stop":1250.408,"duration":42.65}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"But they have their money and that's the --","start":1250.408,"stop":1251.961,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I know but that they have their money and don't know whether they have the right --","start":1251.961,"stop":1255.185,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as to --","start":1255.185,"stop":1255.768,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to pocket it or keep it, they have to do something about it.","start":1255.768,"stop":1258.014,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"As -- all right.","start":1258.014,"stop":1258.989,"duration":0.98},{"text":"But that's --","start":1258.989,"stop":1259.002,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right?(Voice Overlap) --","start":1259.002,"stop":1259.811,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that's --","start":1259.811,"stop":1260.341,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of fact.(Voice Overlap) --","start":1260.341,"stop":1261.106,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true.","start":1261.106,"stop":1261.76,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- before you argue consequently.","start":1261.76,"stop":1263.409,"duration":1.65},{"text":"Is that true that if you -- if the Government is right, and I'm not saying it isn't.","start":1263.409,"stop":1268.359,"duration":4.95},{"text":"I thought that was (Inaudible) that -- that there is a contingency.","start":1268.359,"stop":1275.33,"duration":6.97},{"text":"Where it gets the money, it must make appropriate provision, bookkeeping or whatnot, to keep that amount of money in reserve because non constat, there has -- it has to prove that it properly sent that bill.","start":1275.33,"stop":1289.381,"duration":14.05}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1289.381,"stop":1289.803,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1289.803,"stop":1289.878,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"But that -- that is -- that's a fact.","start":1289.878,"stop":1292.406,"duration":2.53},{"text":"But in overall -- but, we submit first of all, of course, that there is, as they would know from experience, a relatively small percentage of bills which --","start":1292.406,"stop":1300.803,"duration":8.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't (Voice Overlap) --","start":1300.803,"stop":1301.059,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"-- aren't challenged.","start":1301.059,"stop":1302.219,"duration":1.16},{"text":"And on overall basis, this does not require the railroads to keep large sums of money in reserve.","start":1302.219,"stop":1307.061,"duration":4.84},{"text":"But the fact is that this is a consequence which stems from this special privilege which has been extended to this one class of claimants as against all other classes.","start":1307.061,"stop":1317.646,"duration":10.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought I've asked (Inaudible)","start":1317.646,"stop":1319.719,"duration":2.07},{"text":"I thought that we were asked to review this because it's the case that was --","start":1319.719,"stop":1324.474,"duration":4.75}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are -- that -- that is correct.","start":1324.474,"stop":1326.5,"duration":2.03},{"text":"This is a test case of -- there are 40 some odd other cases similarly involved --","start":1326.5,"stop":1330.845,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) we're talking about or is it?","start":1330.845,"stop":1333.942,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"No, this is -- this is, indeed, a -- a test case.","start":1333.942,"stop":1337.207,"duration":3.27},{"text":"Now, the -- the effect --","start":1337.207,"stop":1338.466,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1338.466,"stop":1340.006,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"The effect of the court -- of the holding below is to place the -- the Government now in the position of having to undertake the investigation of all carrier claims which are presented against it that the burden is now shifted to the Government affirmatively to disprove all of the representations which the carriers make in connection with their own bills.","start":1340.006,"stop":1361.394,"duration":21.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But if you say this is only a relative small fact, that's not a great burden on you --","start":1361.394,"stop":1365.83,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1365.83,"stop":1365.902,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- there isn't anymore out there.","start":1365.902,"stop":1366.955,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- we submit that is --","start":1366.955,"stop":1368.424,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1368.424,"stop":1368.558,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in terms of anyone railroad, it is not a large burden.","start":1368.558,"stop":1372.184,"duration":3.63},{"text":"In the statistics which were set forth in a footnote in our brief, footnote 19 on page 25, indicate that in one particular year which was selected, there were over 600,000 vouchers audited and which resulted in 25,000 -- with almost 26,000 notices of overpayment.","start":1372.184,"stop":1392.751,"duration":20.57},{"text":"Now, in terms of any individual carrier, and there are large numbers in the United States, that is not too significant.","start":1392.751,"stop":1398.984,"duration":6.23},{"text":"In terms of place in the -- the obligation on the Government, and every one of those vouchers carries -- not paid them for presentation, every one of those vouchers, the Government now under the holdings below would be obligated to go out and affirmatively disprove.","start":1398.984,"stop":1411.271,"duration":12.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what it practically (Inaudible) practically about these things, what it --","start":1411.271,"stop":1415.442,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That --","start":1415.442,"stop":1415.677,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) every voucher would have to be independent in a large (Inaudible) it has to be at work?","start":1415.677,"stop":1423.474,"duration":7.8}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's -- there's no -- there's no question that it would be an increase burden.","start":1423.474,"stop":1429.003,"duration":5.53},{"text":"The extent to which it would be increased would depend impart upon how many of the particular disputes resolved were -- were involved rather questions of fact and also, I suppose, upon the degree to which the railroads will cooperate.","start":1429.003,"stop":1442.78,"duration":13.78},{"text":"But the fact is that --","start":1442.78,"stop":1443.334,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) I conceive that the force -- the magnitude of this problem on either side.","start":1443.334,"stop":1447.784,"duration":4.45},{"text":"That's what I'm (Inaudible)","start":1447.784,"stop":1451.354,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Rosenthal, I gather in essence that your argument comes down to this, that before 322, whenever an issue of overcharge arose, the burden was upon the railroads to sustain its complaint.","start":1451.354,"stop":1464.611,"duration":13.26}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1464.611,"stop":1465.122,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And that all the 322 did, adapted for the convenience of the carriers so that they'd get their money little earlier than otherwise they did, made no change in the instance where issues of overcharge, the road --","start":1465.122,"stop":1477.922,"duration":12.8}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That's --","start":1477.922,"stop":1478.074,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it still had the burden upon the carrier to establish the claims.","start":1478.074,"stop":1480.898,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- that is --","start":1480.898,"stop":1481.737,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that it?","start":1481.737,"stop":1482.214,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"-- precisely, Mr. Justice Brennan, our position.","start":1482.214,"stop":1485.155,"duration":2.94},{"text":"That -- and we think that again that the legislative history in background of the statute, the terms of the statute itself --","start":1485.155,"stop":1490.962,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as a practical matter, when issues of overcharge arise, I suppose most of them are resolved by negotiation between the carrier and the Government.","start":1490.962,"stop":1498.744,"duration":7.78}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1498.744,"stop":1499.833,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And these things arise only when the issue persists and hasn't been resolved between the party?","start":1499.833,"stop":1504.973,"duration":5.14}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that would be solved.","start":1504.973,"stop":1506.95,"duration":1.98},{"text":"Of course, in this case --","start":1506.95,"stop":1507.312,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And will that run anything like 25,000 years?","start":1507.312,"stop":1510.056,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there was -- there's no breakdown on -- as to how what percentage of these overpayments involved questions of fact.","start":1510.056,"stop":1517.748,"duration":7.69},{"text":"Now, there are a number of cases presently pending, what percentage their represent, I do not know, which involved this question of the availability of cars.","start":1517.748,"stop":1528.398,"duration":10.65},{"text":"As to -- as to those cases, of course, this question is -- is foremost.","start":1528.398,"stop":1535.234,"duration":6.84},{"text":"If the Court pleases, I --","start":1535.234,"stop":1537.152,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask one question.","start":1537.152,"stop":1539.356,"duration":2.2},{"text":"I understand (Inaudible)","start":1539.356,"stop":1554.395,"duration":15.04}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1554.395,"stop":1554.842,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) but it doesn't give the Government -- the Government (Inaudible)","start":1554.842,"stop":1564.796,"duration":9.95}]},{"speakerName":"Alan S. Rosenthal","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely not, that as this statute has been consistently interpreted by the General Accounting Office, it imposes a mandatory duty upon the fiscal offices of the Government to pay those bills as long as, upon presentation, as long as on the face.","start":1564.796,"stop":1580.033,"duration":15.24},{"text":"There's -- there's no objection to them.","start":1580.033,"stop":1586.655,"duration":6.62}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Sweeney.","start":1586.655,"stop":1588.23,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, Justices, may it please the Court.","start":1588.23,"stop":1592.91,"duration":4.68},{"text":"When this case started off, it was on a very elemental claim.","start":1592.91,"stop":1597.736,"duration":4.83},{"text":"We thought that we were suing on a simple contract to collect transportation charges for services that we rendered in 1950.","start":1597.736,"stop":1607.447,"duration":9.71},{"text":"At the outset, the Government filed what -- what really purported to be a general denial of the charges in 1950.","start":1607.447,"stop":1618.707,"duration":11.26},{"text":"Subsequently, however, they filed a substitute answer.","start":1618.707,"stop":1622.891,"duration":4.18},{"text":"And then, in that answer, they said, \"All right.","start":1622.891,"stop":1625.066,"duration":2.17},{"text":"We admit.","start":1625.066,"stop":1626.678,"duration":1.61},{"text":"You did perform those charges -- those services.","start":1626.678,"stop":1630.349,"duration":3.67},{"text":"Those charges were proper.","start":1630.349,"stop":1632.429,"duration":2.08},{"text":"And you are due those charges.","start":1632.429,"stop":1634.942,"duration":2.51},{"text":"However, we have paid you, they said.","start":1634.942,"stop":1637.333,"duration":2.39},{"text":"\"We paid you a check of $117 and some odd, and then we have taken out over $1000 which is our right under 322, Section 322 of the Transportation Act because six years prior in 1944, you furnished cars that were longer than the size of cars ordered.\"","start":1637.333,"stop":1660.792,"duration":23.46},{"text":"And we say -- we have determined that there were cars available of the right size.","start":1660.792,"stop":1666.39,"duration":5.6},{"text":"So therefore, we claimed a credit for the difference.","start":1666.39,"stop":1669.913,"duration":3.52},{"text":"Now, that point, of course, the elemental part of the case began to back down because as the right way, the Government then said to the District Court, \"The railroad cannot, in anyway, claim relief here because they have not alleged the facts which would show that our claim as to the 1944 situation was true.\"","start":1669.913,"stop":1695.704,"duration":25.79},{"text":"And the railroad rebelled.","start":1695.704,"stop":1696.902,"duration":1.2},{"text":"That railroad said, \"We do not have to allege in any suit for a 1950 charge that we did not -- we're not overpaid in 1944.\"","start":1696.902,"stop":1708.797,"duration":11.89},{"text":"The thing hinged -- the -- the case hinged on that point and the Government refused to go forward any proof and so the claim is filed for summary judgment, would grant a summary judgment on the basis that there was no factual issue outstanding as to the 1950 charges.","start":1708.797,"stop":1726.797,"duration":18},{"text":"And that as to the allegations in regard to 1944, they were a -- an affirmative defense.","start":1726.797,"stop":1734.756,"duration":7.96},{"text":"They were a set off by way of counterclaim and that the Government had the burden of proof, so held the District Court and so held the First Circuit on appeal.","start":1734.756,"stop":1749.842,"duration":15.09},{"text":"Now, the Government's position is based solely upon the fact that all of these new rights in judicial procedure come to the Government by virtue of the provisions of 322, Section 322 of the Transportation Act.","start":1749.842,"stop":1770.29,"duration":20.45},{"text":"And we say, and our position here today is, that it is neither just nor reasonable nor, in any way, necessary to attribute those particular properties through Section 322 and that those provisions are not nor can they be read into Section 322.","start":1770.29,"stop":1792.367,"duration":22.08}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Sweeney, how -- how -- assuming you're right, how does the Government get its money back if it was overcharged?","start":1792.367,"stop":1799.734,"duration":7.37}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Government was overcharged and it can proved in it set off that we have the cars available in 1944, then they -- their setoff would be allowed against our charges of 1950.","start":1799.734,"stop":1811.668,"duration":11.93}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do they'd have to go out and affirmatively prove then the --","start":1811.668,"stop":1814.46,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1814.46,"stop":1814.846,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- fact that --","start":1814.846,"stop":1815.251,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1815.251,"stop":1815.843,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- upon which they based the allegation of both.","start":1815.843,"stop":1818.205,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1818.205,"stop":1818.952,"duration":0.75},{"text":"Now --","start":1818.952,"stop":1819.032,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But you didn't -- which was not the case before 322.","start":1819.032,"stop":1823.001,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"It was not the case, Your Honor, because it would never arise.","start":1823.001,"stop":1825.693,"duration":2.69},{"text":"You see --","start":1825.693,"stop":1826.437,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but before 322, as I understand it, the practice was if you submitted a bill that was pre-audited and the Government said, \"You've overcharged this by $1100,\" then it'd be the railroad's burden to establish in court that in fact, there was no overcharge.","start":1826.437,"stop":1842.305,"duration":15.87}]},{"speakerName":"Edmund M. Sweeney","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1842.305,"stop":1843.436,"duration":1.13},{"text":"There are two points I'd like to bring out here though.","start":1843.436,"stop":1845.464,"duration":2.03},{"text":"First of all, it was an unfair advantage to be given to the Government as a shipper because once the Government was in commerce, they should be just like any other shipper.","start":1845.464,"stop":1854.173,"duration":8.71},{"text":"And the -- and the rule provided that the other shipper had to pay us upon delivery.","start":1854.173,"stop":1857.835,"duration":3.66},{"text":"Actually, I honestly believe that a railroad, at any time, could just stop serving the Government until they were paid like any other shipper, but, of course, naturally, they wouldn't.","start":1857.835,"stop":1867.308,"duration":9.47},{"text":"Now, the second point I would like to make on that is this.","start":1867.308,"stop":1870.36,"duration":3.05},{"text":"That the Government has placed great reliance upon what now has become to be a tenant of this, tenant of this, and that is this.","start":1870.36,"stop":1882.768,"duration":12.41},{"text":"That it is traditional that everybody that has a claim against the Government must prove it.","start":1882.768,"stop":1891.271,"duration":8.5},{"text":"Well, now, we believe that, and we could have sued on the deduction itself.","start":1891.271,"stop":1897.025,"duration":5.75},{"text":"And if we had sued on the deduction, we would have to prove whether or not we have the cars available.","start":1897.025,"stop":1903.335,"duration":6.31},{"text":"But I say that 322, in no way, permits me or prohibits me from choosing the forum in which I wish to go in.","start":1903.335,"stop":1913.122,"duration":9.79},{"text":"And I also say that it does not, in any way change, the judicial rules which allows the plaintiff to frame the issue.","start":1913.122,"stop":1922.099,"duration":8.98},{"text":"Now, the Government is trying to claim here that 322 changes all the -- the fundamentals of practice and procedure in that whenever the Government appears as a counter claimant against the railroad that all rules are on, new rules are on that the railroad then has to disprove the Government's case.","start":1922.099,"stop":1947.235,"duration":25.14},{"text":"And we respectfully submit that that certainly would not be.","start":1947.235,"stop":1956.978,"duration":9.74}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Nov 20, 1957","petitioner":"United States","respondent":"New York, New Haven & Hartford Railroad Company","docket":"45","citation":"355 US 253 (1957)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/355/253","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Dec 16, 1957"}